node.title: Security forces fire tear gas, arrest doens of protesters in Burkina Faso
node.description: Protesters are angry at the government's inability to stem violence linked to Al Qaeda and the Islamic State group.

node.title: 'Young people are written off too quickly': These candidates say it's time for change
node.description: People under 30 are the most under-represented in New South Wales local government, but young candidates running in the December 4 election are determined to address that.

node.title: Meet the family building a desert dynasty in the Red Centre
node.description: Angus and Kimberley McKay are quietly building a cattle empire in the desert, making bold purchases and adopting a prudent cattle management plan to look after their land.

node.title: James sought a CT scan to explain his constant headaches. What they found had 'a bunch of people panicking'
node.description: James Enaver says the first signs that he was ill were the persistent headaches that started three years ago. Now, a fundraising effort by friends and family has led to Tasmania's first tumour biobank.

node.title: Beware the humble mango — it can leave its nasty mark
node.description: Mango sap is a nightmare for farmers and a serious issue for locals. Fruit pickers in the Kimberley are being warned to watch out for the fruit's often painful surprise.

node.title: Victoria's 2022 election is Labor's to lose, but the 'red wall' in Melbourne's west is changing
node.description: For years, Labor has been able to rely on a swag of votes through Melbourne's west. But shifting boundaries and changing demographics suggest rusted-on Labor backers may have an appetite for fresh political voices to champion their communities.

node.title: Elopement is on the rise but could it be a pandemic trend?
node.description: The COVID pandemic may have kickstarted it but there's a growing trend for couples choosing to elope, with surprising results.

node.title: Alleged abduction of baby leaves woman critically injured on Gold Coast
node.description: Police find a woman unresponsive in a Gold Coast apartment and allege a baby was taken before being found hours later.

node.title: After 13 days of searching for William Tyrrell, authorities have uncovered more questions
node.description: After seven years, it has come down to an area of bush about the size of four football fields. But two weeks in to the renewed search for William Tyrrell, the main things uncovered are more questions.

node.title: Regional NSW in flooding firing line, but some communities are spared the worst
node.description: Another anxious night has passed for flood-affected residents of several regional NSW towns and rural areas, with residents of Singleton in the Hunter Valley counting their blessings after the Hunter River peaked lower than feared.

node.title: Genomic testing for Omicron underway after infected South African passengers touch down in Sydney
node.description: Urgent genomic testing is underway to determine if infected passengers who arrived in Sydney from South Africa contracted the Omicron COVID-19 variant.

node.title: Many pharmacies will now print hard copies of vaccine passes
node.description: People who cannot get their vaccine pass online, can now visit a pharmacy to have a hard copy printed out.

node.title: Alice Waters Helps a Museum Cater to the Tastes of Art Lovers
node.description: A new restaurant at the Hammer Museum in Los Angeles is the latest effort to try to reach visitors’ hearts through their stomachs.

node.title: Republicans Have a Golden Opportunity. They Will Probably Blow It.
node.description: The party’s good fortune in avoiding profound punishment for all its follies is the reason  those follies will probably continue.

node.title: North Carolina’s Furniture Hub Is Booming. What Comes Next?
node.description: The furniture capital of the state is ground zero for inflation, labor shortages, hot demand and limited supply. It’s debating how to cope.

node.title: Christina says a routine breast check saved her life. She's worried other women are missing out
node.description: In parts of Australia hit by COVID-19 lockdowns, women could wait months for breast cancer screens. Doctors say they have a way to ease the backlog, but they need government support.

node.title: 2023 Women's World Cup is already changing the game for First Nations communities
node.description: The 2023 Women's World Cup is the first to use Indigenous languages in its official identity, hinting at work beneath the surface to further embrace and support First Nations communities.

node.title: A stranger told Jennelle she shouldn't have children. Now she's a proud mum
node.description: One of the biggest challenges for parents with blindness or low vision can be negative attitudes from others. But with support from peers and a bit of planning, these women have navigated motherhood and found immense love and joy.

node.title: Get Back: Peter Jackson's epic Beatles documentary dispels myths about the band's final year
node.description: Peter Jackson’s epic eight-hour series shows the band's camaraderie and creative genius even in their death throes.

node.title: ‘You’re not bouncy enough to have ADHD’: Australian school kids say ADHD is severely misunderstood
node.description: ADHD affects one in 20 Australian children, which means, statistically, there is a child with ADHD in every single classroom in the country. But a recent study shows 55 per cent of teachers do not have adequate training on managing ADHD in the classroom.

node.title: 'There have been rumours': Why the next two years could decide the fate of Kim Jong Un
node.description: North Korea claims to have been COVID-free for the duration of the pandemic. But recent events south of the border could have major implications for the secretive nation and its enigmatic ruler.

node.title: House prices depend on interest rates: As one goes up, the other will fall
node.description: House price falls are all but baked in as interest rates start rising over the next couple of years. How much prices fall mainly depends on how high and quickly borrowing costs end up rising, writes Michael Janda.

node.title: Omicron 'may already be here in Australia'. Experts say there's more we can do to stop COVID
node.description: The emergence of the Omicron variant of coronavirus shows Africa needs greater access to vaccines, experts say. There are also warnings we shouldn't give up masks, social distancing or contact tracing in Australia.

node.title: Chris Christie Touts 'Talent' to Be President, Undaunted by Trump Hinting at 2024 Run
node.description: The former Republican governor of New Jersey said he's "not ready to retire."

node.title: Michael never told anyone about the thoughts in his head until they landed him in prison
node.description: All Michael wanted as a kid was for the bad thoughts to go away. And one day they did, but the reason why led him down a dark path.

node.title: Fauci says he "would not be surprised" if new COVID variant is in U.S.
node.description: "When you have a virus like this, it almost invariably is ultimately going to go essentially all over," Fauci said.

node.title: Mets Owner Blasts Agent Over Matz’s Decision to Sign Elsewhere
node.description: The club hoped Steven Matz would return after rejuvenating his career in Toronto. Much to Steven Cohen’s chagrin, Matz chose St. Louis instead.

node.title: A Tale of Culinary Reconciliation, Beside the Eiffel Tower
node.description: Two decades ago, Spain was the new France, leading gastronomic innovation. Now two iconic chefs have joined forces in Paris.

node.title: How an ancient message shows the path to protecting Aboriginal communities from COVID-19
node.description: If the urgent problems fuelling COVID-19 outbreaks in Indigenous communities aren't addressed, things will continue to go poorly for First Nations people across Australia, writes Tynan King.

node.title: What do Australia's great novels have in common?
node.description: A new three-part documentary series puts Australian literature firmly in the spotlight, and asks the question: can books help us understand our country?
